    {
        "type": "highlight",
        "timestamp": "2024-10-20T00:21:31.356Z",
        "text": "Sneezing is a crucial bodily function that serves as a protective mechanism, helping to flush out old cells and particulates from our nasal cavity. This process is initiated by a sneeze gene and is facilitated by a small compound in our nasal cavity. The sneeze signal is processed by the hippocampus in our brain, which leads to reflexive muscle contractions. These contractions determine the speed of the sneeze, and holding back a sneeze can damage the surface of our nose and sinus.\n\nMas Takashma, chair of the Department of Otolaryngology, Head and Neck Surgery at Houston Methodist Academic Institute, and Sheena Cruikshank, a professor in the University of Manchester’s Division of Immunology, both explain that sneezing also helps the immune system in protecting from viruses. The volume of a sneeze is determined by the structure of our respiratory system, including the shape and \"floppiness\" of our vocal cords and other soft tissues at the back of the throat.\n\nHowever, cultural factors, psychological factors, and societal norms can also influence the sound of a sneeze. Takashma notes that in Japan, where there is a heavy cultural emphasis on not inconveniencing others, people manage to suppress their sneezes. This is achieved by minimizing the amount of resonant energy flowing through the oral cavity, essentially by keeping the mouth closed. This method is also the most effective way to sneeze quietly.",
