    {
        "type": "paste",
        "timestamp": "2024-10-20T00:29:06.453Z",
        "text": "Sneezing is a critical bodily function that serves as a protective mechanism, helping to flush out old cells and particulates from our nasal cavity. A sneeze begins when epithelial cells begin to collect a large amount of dust and other irritants in the mucus of our noses. At high levels, this wakes up immune cells in the nose that kicks off a response. The body makes more mucus, swelling starts in the nose, and signals are sent to the brain via the trigeminal nerve, which provides sensation to the face. This signal is processed by an area at the base of our brain called the medulla oblongata, resulting in reflexive muscle contractions.\n\nHowever, this doesn't determine the volume of a sneeze. Instead, this is tied to the shape of your vocal cords and lung size. When we inhale for a sneeze, the vocal cords close tight until there is enough pressure to push the air back out with all the particulates, at which point the floppiness of the vocal cords that the air passes determines the sound generated.\n\nAdditionally, cultural factors, psychological factors, and societal norms can also influence the sound of a sneeze. Mas Takashima, the chair of the Department of Otolaryngology, Head and Neck Surgery at Houston Methodist Academic Institute, notes that in Japan, where there is a heavy cultural emphasis on not inconveniencing others, people manage to suppress their sneezes. This is achieved by minimizing the amount of resonant energy flowing through the oral cavity, essentially by keeping the mouth closed. This method is also the most effective way to sneeze quietly.",
